He lived in Paris and in London and was awarded the Prix de Rome in 1823 as well as the Légion d'honneur in 1862.
In 1823, after having won the Prix de Rome, he travelled to England for the first time to give several solo concerts, also including Ireland.
This was followed by travels to Switzerland and Italy, before he returned to France in 1831.
In 1837, he married the singer Mlle.

He was conductor of the Opéra Comique between 1847 and 1849, afterwards "inspecteur accompagnateur" of the Imperial Chapel of Napoléon III, and finally (from 1867), professor of harp at the Conservatoire.
